-- TIMELINE-British steps to deal with the financial crisis
-- 
-- Wed Oct 8, 2008 7:48am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/08/us-financial-britain-banks-chron-idUSTRE49735C20081008

 

 Oct 8 - Britain said it would inject 50 billion pounds ($87.2 billion) of capital into its banks on Wednesday to help stabilize the country's financial system. 

 Below are some of the key steps taken by Britain since the beginning of the financial crisis last year: September 14, 2007 - Northern Rock says the Bank of England has stepped in to support it, triggering the first run on a major bank in more than a century, despite reassurances from regulators the lender is not bust. February 17, 2008 - Northern Rock is nationalized after funding crisis. April 22 - The Bank of England unveils a plan to swap banks' risky mortgage assets for at least 50 billion pounds of government debt. September 17 - Lloyds TSB Group Plc agrees to rescue rival HBOS Plc, scooping up Britain's biggest home loan lender in an all-share deal, facilitated by the government. September 18 - The Financial Services Authority imposes a temporary ban on short-selling financial stocks, a measure copied elsewhere. September 29 - Nationalization of mortgage lender Bradford & Bingley Plc is announced. Spain's Banco Santander SA will buy its retail deposits and branch network. October 8 - Finance Minister Alistair Darling injects up to 50 billion pounds of government money into the country's banks. (Reporting by  Avril Ormsby , editing by Will Waterman)